WEBVTT

00:01.127 --> 00:02.698
- Look at...
- Oh, he's so cute.

00:02.746 --> 00:04.278
Of course he is. He's half Natalie.

00:04.303 --> 00:06.008
- Look.
- Aww!

00:06.033 --> 00:07.286
So precious.

00:07.311 --> 00:08.679
Oh, and would you look at that.

00:08.704 --> 00:10.560
He got my eyelashes.

00:10.585 --> 00:12.643
You delivered him.
That doesn't give him your DNA.

00:12.668 --> 00:14.631
You'd be surprised. The power of these hands.

00:14.656 --> 00:15.877
You can sign out
the patient in four.

00:15.902 --> 00:17.965
- Look... look at Owen.
- Cute.

00:17.990 --> 00:19.414
Have you been up to see
Natalie today?

00:19.439 --> 00:21.806
- Not yet.
- What's up with him?

00:21.808 --> 00:23.174
Thought he wouldn't leave
her bedside.

00:23.176 --> 00:24.975
[phone rings]

00:24.977 --> 00:28.046
- Dr. Zanetti.
- Dr. Rhodes.

00:28.071 --> 00:29.457
How was the conference?

00:29.482 --> 00:30.614
I spent an entire week

00:30.616 --> 00:32.116
listening to people
talk about surgeries.

00:32.118 --> 00:34.454
All I wanted was
to actually do one.

00:34.479 --> 00:36.125
Kept hoping a speaker would
choke on his dentures

00:36.150 --> 00:38.099
- so I could cric him.
- Dinner tonight?

00:38.124 --> 00:39.800
I can't. I'm in-house on call.

00:39.825 --> 00:43.041
Head's up. Incoming traumas.
CFD called with a Plan 1.

00:43.066 --> 00:45.512
Multi-victim car crash. Let's go!

00:45.537 --> 00:47.007
Maybe someone'll need surgery.

00:47.032 --> 00:48.539
I'm ready to cut.

00:49.012 --> 00:52.113
- What do we got?
- Female, mid-20s. GCS 3.

00:52.138 --> 00:54.305
Struck the dashboard
and starred the windshield.

00:54.330 --> 00:55.929
- BP?
- Uh, 90 over 50.

00:55.954 --> 00:58.323
Tachy 140. Stats 100%.

00:58.348 --> 01:00.548
Pressure dressing on her head,
but she's seeping through.

01:00.573 --> 01:02.640
All right, we're gonna replace
the King with an ET.

01:02.665 --> 01:03.836
Grab an intubation kit.

01:03.861 --> 01:05.001
Let's move her on my count.

01:05.027 --> 01:06.605
One... two... three.

01:06.630 --> 01:08.630
<i>[sirens blare]</i>

01:08.655 --> 01:09.769
Jess?

01:10.567 --> 01:12.833
- Jess... Jess...
- Mike Carter, 24.

01:12.858 --> 01:15.611
- GCS 10. Vitals holding steady.
- Jess?

01:15.636 --> 01:16.716
- Blood?
- Not his.

01:16.741 --> 01:18.153
Jess, talk to me!

01:18.178 --> 01:20.002
- Jess!
- Mike. Mike.

01:20.027 --> 01:21.693
I'm gonna ask you to calm down.

01:21.718 --> 01:23.852
Jess!
Where is she?

01:23.877 --> 01:25.351
- Where is she?
- Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

01:25.376 --> 01:27.672
You have to lie back down.

01:27.850 --> 01:29.192
Easy.

01:29.474 --> 01:31.853
- All right, on my count.
- All right.

01:31.878 --> 01:34.135
One... two... three.

01:35.022 --> 01:37.890
Does Jess have any family
in the area we should notify?

01:37.915 --> 01:41.118
I think... her mom lives here.
Maybe.

01:41.143 --> 01:43.476
- Any allergies to medications?
- I don't know.

01:43.501 --> 01:45.065
Do you know if she's currently
on any medication?

01:45.090 --> 01:45.964
I don't know.

01:45.989 --> 01:47.720
Is there anything
you can tell us about Jess

01:47.745 --> 01:50.179
that could help us?
No. I'm sorry, I...

01:50.204 --> 01:52.615
I don't even know
where she lives.

01:52.640 --> 01:55.008
We're on a first date.

01:57.825 --> 02:02.967
- Synced and corrected by martythecrazy -
- www.addic7ed.com -

02:04.912 --> 02:06.955
Breath sounds good
on both sides.

02:06.980 --> 02:07.898
- Good color change.
- All right.

02:07.923 --> 02:09.892
She is still bleeding
pretty bad.

02:09.917 --> 02:12.031
- Hang two units of blood.
- Yes, Doctor.

02:12.056 --> 02:13.322
- Get me a plastics tray.
- Got it.

02:13.324 --> 02:14.934
We need to stop these bleeders.

02:14.959 --> 02:17.259
- Saline?
- Got it. Here's saline.

02:19.200 --> 02:21.434
Okay, she's still got
glass shards in her scalp.

02:21.459 --> 02:23.158
- Heart rate is erratic.
- Suction.

02:23.183 --> 02:24.983
Yeah, got it.

02:26.199 --> 02:27.279
<i>[monitors beeping]</i>

02:27.304 --> 02:29.338
Please, I need to know
how she is.

02:29.340 --> 02:30.415
Jess is in good hands.

02:30.440 --> 02:32.051
Right now, we just need
to make sure that you're okay.

02:32.076 --> 02:33.586
I'm fine, just please, help her.

02:33.611 --> 02:35.020
Ah!

02:35.045 --> 02:36.545
Sorry.
I'm guessing that's tender.

02:36.570 --> 02:38.064
Ah. Yes.

02:38.139 --> 02:40.074
- Pressure's falling.
- Get me the ultrasound.

02:40.105 --> 02:42.050
- Got it.
- Call pharmacy.

02:42.075 --> 02:44.675
Get dopamine going.

02:44.700 --> 02:47.758
[overlapping chatter]

02:50.449 --> 02:51.815
There's free fluid
in her abdomen.

02:51.929 --> 02:53.161
Pressure's still low.

02:53.163 --> 02:55.464
She's not stable enough
to go to CT.

02:55.466 --> 02:56.765
We need to open her up now.

02:56.767 --> 02:58.066
Call the OR and tell them
we're on our way up.

02:58.068 --> 02:59.684
Yes, Doctor.

02:59.709 --> 03:02.928
- Talk to me.
- Walter Blevins. 53 years old.

03:02.953 --> 03:06.622
GCS 14, SBP 104 over palp.
Stats 100.

03:06.647 --> 03:08.921
- Dr. Halstead, Treatment 1.
- Got it.

03:08.946 --> 03:11.598
4 of morphine per
the tele doctor.

03:11.623 --> 03:14.338
- Ah.
- Let's rotate.

03:15.022 --> 03:16.629
Give him the head.
Give him the head.

03:16.654 --> 03:17.953
- Let's go.
- What happened?

03:17.955 --> 03:19.488
He was driving the car that t-boned

03:19.513 --> 03:21.921
the couple they just brought in.
A stolen car.

03:22.026 --> 03:24.192
On my count.
One... two... three.

03:24.217 --> 03:24.803
Transfer.

03:24.828 --> 03:26.183
- Get this out.
- [moans]

03:26.208 --> 03:27.929
Airway's intact.

03:27.954 --> 03:29.887
Let's get him off that
backboard.

03:29.912 --> 03:32.847
Mr. Blevins, we're gonna
roll you onto your right side.

03:32.872 --> 03:34.671
I need you
to take these handcuffs off.

03:34.696 --> 03:36.423
He carjacked a woman at gunpoint

03:36.448 --> 03:38.050
50 yards from me and my partner.

03:38.075 --> 03:40.096
Led us on a high-speed chase
before hitting that couple.

03:40.121 --> 03:42.054
- This guy's dangerous.
- I'll take my chances.

03:42.079 --> 03:43.945
He served nine years
for armed robbery.

03:43.970 --> 03:45.932
- He's an ex-con.
- He's also my patient.

03:45.957 --> 03:48.001
I can't treat him properly
until the cuffs are off.

03:48.026 --> 03:49.831
All right.

03:49.857 --> 03:53.358
- Dr. Halstead, you got this?
- Yeah, we're good.

03:54.416 --> 03:55.716
[groans]

03:56.105 --> 03:57.437
Ah...

03:57.462 --> 03:59.529
All right.

03:59.554 --> 04:01.120
- Okay, you're all right.
- [groans]

04:01.145 --> 04:02.612
- Any pain on contact?
- No.

04:02.641 --> 04:04.761
Good.

04:04.786 --> 04:07.243
I'm sorry.

04:09.701 --> 04:11.865
Oh, Dr. Halstead, his arm.

04:11.890 --> 04:13.825
- [heavy breathing]
- All right. Yep.

04:13.850 --> 04:16.284
That's likely a two-bone
forearm fracture.

04:16.309 --> 04:17.575
Let's get an X-ray.

04:17.600 --> 04:20.721
- Lap sponges, keep 'em coming.
- Yes, Doctor.

04:20.747 --> 04:22.047
There's too much blood.

04:22.072 --> 04:23.538
I can't see
where it's coming from.

04:23.563 --> 04:24.729
- Feel for it.
- [monitor beeps]

04:24.754 --> 04:25.819
Pressure's dropping.

04:25.844 --> 04:27.444
Dr. Rhodes, I'll clamp.

04:27.469 --> 04:30.170
The belly's packed.
The spleen is in pieces.

04:30.195 --> 04:32.728
- Something else is bleeding.
- Okay.

04:32.753 --> 04:34.954
Run the bowel.

04:36.705 --> 04:38.539
Oh, the mesentery's bleeding.

04:38.564 --> 04:41.659
I will clamp it, Dr. Rhodes.
You get the spleen.

04:41.684 --> 04:43.966
Curved 8 to me.

04:43.991 --> 04:46.925
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

04:46.950 --> 04:49.150
<i>♪
♪</i>

04:49.175 --> 04:52.036
- Metz scissors.
- Scissors.

04:56.646 --> 04:58.947
- And bowl.
- Bowl.

04:59.124 --> 05:02.492
Thank you.
I'll hold the clamp, you tie.

05:05.301 --> 05:06.977
All right, the bleeding stopped.

05:07.002 --> 05:08.001
How's she doing?

05:08.026 --> 05:09.692
Pressure's coming up.

05:09.717 --> 05:12.618
- There we go.
- Okay.

05:12.643 --> 05:14.710
You guys finish up here

05:14.735 --> 05:17.636
and bring her down to ICU.

05:17.661 --> 05:18.827
Okay, let's close him up.

05:18.852 --> 05:20.694
Happy to be back in the saddle?

05:20.719 --> 05:22.279
Boo-yah.

05:24.439 --> 05:26.673
April. Nice to see you.

05:26.698 --> 05:29.332
Bobby, back so soon?

05:29.357 --> 05:31.932
Yeah, my feet this time.

05:31.956 --> 05:33.635
What happened to your shoes?

05:33.660 --> 05:35.775
There's this new guy
at the shelter.

05:35.800 --> 05:37.433
He needed winter boots.

05:37.458 --> 05:39.492
I still have my slippers,
though.

05:39.663 --> 05:41.129
All right, this is
a tetanus shot.

05:41.154 --> 05:42.526
- Is that okay?
- Oh.

05:42.551 --> 05:43.850
Anything you say.

05:43.875 --> 05:46.843
- Okay. Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

05:48.450 --> 05:50.817
All right.

05:50.842 --> 05:52.791
Now, Bobby, you shouldn't be
giving away your boots.

05:52.816 --> 05:54.308
Particularly in January.

05:54.333 --> 05:56.166
Oh, I'll manage.
I always do.

05:56.191 --> 05:58.758
How did you manage last week
after you gave away your gloves?

05:58.783 --> 06:02.184
- Frostbite's all healed.
- You're too much.

06:02.209 --> 06:04.944
All right, soak your feet.

06:07.179 --> 06:09.223
Ah.

06:09.248 --> 06:12.216
- I'll be back to check on you.
- Okay. Thanks.

06:13.787 --> 06:16.442
That excuse is so lame
it needs crutches.

06:16.467 --> 06:18.916
Roger, I put in that order
hours ago.

06:18.941 --> 06:20.806
No, I will not hold.

06:21.651 --> 06:23.017
Roger?

06:23.042 --> 06:24.756
Rog?

06:25.013 --> 06:27.102
Oh.

06:27.299 --> 06:28.958
Normally after that,
I would go downstairs

06:28.983 --> 06:30.326
and ring Roger's ass.

06:30.351 --> 06:31.517
But not today.

06:31.542 --> 06:32.607
I'm in too good a mood.

06:32.632 --> 06:34.065
And why is that?

06:34.117 --> 06:35.650
Christy Pierce.

06:35.675 --> 06:38.075
Oh, yeah.
Today's the big day.

06:38.100 --> 06:39.566
- Uh-huh.
- Christy Pierce?

06:39.591 --> 06:42.326
Yeah, a teen
with aplastic anemia.

06:42.351 --> 06:44.351
Been in and out of Med
the last ten years

06:44.376 --> 06:46.409
due to infections, but finally,

06:46.434 --> 06:49.015
today she's getting
a bone marrow transplant.

06:49.040 --> 06:51.069
- It hasn't been ten years.
- Yes, it has.

06:51.094 --> 06:52.919
I know because I was
sitting in your chair

06:52.944 --> 06:55.111
the first time her mother
brought her here.

06:55.136 --> 06:57.651
You think I'm tough?
You should've seen her.

06:57.676 --> 06:59.476
I'm going up to say hello.

06:59.501 --> 07:01.892
Give Christy a kiss for me.

07:02.230 --> 07:06.466
So Dr. Farinas has told me
that a transplant isn't painful.

07:06.491 --> 07:08.424
You'll be awake the whole time.

07:08.426 --> 07:09.846
It's a simple process.

07:09.871 --> 07:11.671
We'll administer
the donor's stem cells

07:11.696 --> 07:12.862
through your central line.

07:12.887 --> 07:14.353
It's just like
a blood transfusion.

07:14.378 --> 07:17.081
Is it really happening?
Finally.

07:17.106 --> 07:19.306
Well, we just heard
from the clinic in Springfield.

07:19.331 --> 07:20.730
The bags are en route.

07:20.755 --> 07:21.910
Oh, my God.

07:21.935 --> 07:24.873
Mom, you promised.
No crying.

07:24.898 --> 07:26.705
I'm sorry, I just...
I can't help it.

07:26.730 --> 07:29.809
And, Nick, I can't believe you.

07:29.834 --> 07:31.878
You're almost as tall as me.

07:31.903 --> 07:34.260
And he has been
a very busy little brother.

07:34.285 --> 07:35.795
He's got all his friends
together

07:35.820 --> 07:37.587
and they've been shoveling
driveways to raise money.

07:37.589 --> 07:40.756
Oh, show Mrs. Goodwin the flyer.

07:44.423 --> 07:46.369
We're gonna send
Christy's donor and her family

07:46.394 --> 07:49.695
- on a vacation.
- They've already raised $1,000.

07:49.720 --> 07:51.344
That's a sweet gesture.

07:51.369 --> 07:54.237
He's just trying
to build up his muscles

07:54.239 --> 07:56.746
- to impress the girls.
- Am not!

07:56.771 --> 07:59.439
Well, I'll leave you
in good hands with Dr. Farinas.

07:59.464 --> 08:00.629
I'll check back later.

08:00.654 --> 08:02.654
Thank you.

08:04.105 --> 08:07.433
Dr. Rose,
pretty slick in the OR.

08:07.458 --> 08:09.542
Thank you.

08:10.175 --> 08:13.343
That was a very fast
splenectomy for a fellow.

08:13.368 --> 08:15.845
Had to be under 30 seconds.

08:15.870 --> 08:17.111
Where'd you pick that up?

08:17.136 --> 08:18.656
- Riyadh.
- Mm.

08:18.681 --> 08:20.814
Oil workers
got a lot of abdominal injuries

08:20.839 --> 08:22.184
- on the derricks.
- Hmm.

08:22.187 --> 08:23.775
Hold the elevator, please!
Hold the elevator!

08:23.800 --> 08:25.466
Ah! Ow!

08:25.491 --> 08:26.991
- Damn it.
- Sorry. Thanks.

08:27.016 --> 08:28.295
- You okay?
- Yes.

08:28.320 --> 08:30.994
I, um, just banged it
on the shower in Orlando.

08:31.019 --> 08:32.203
- Let me take a look at it.
- No, no, no.

08:32.229 --> 08:33.395
- It's fine.
- No, no.

08:33.421 --> 08:34.654
- It's fine, really.
- Just... hey, hey.

08:34.655 --> 08:36.789
Shush, shush. Just, shh.

08:37.903 --> 08:39.772
<i>[elevator bell dings]</i>

08:39.797 --> 08:41.179
[laughs]

08:41.203 --> 08:43.466
Wait, no. No, no, no.
What are we doing?

08:43.491 --> 08:45.858
You are going to Ortho
to get that checked out.

08:45.883 --> 08:47.438
No, it's not necessary.

08:47.463 --> 08:48.896
Uh, your elbow is red

08:48.921 --> 08:50.495
and it feels hot.
So, yeah, it is.

08:50.520 --> 08:52.853
Yeah, well,
I put myself on Cipro, so...

08:52.878 --> 08:54.377
Oh, so you know
you have an infection?

08:54.402 --> 08:55.827
Just as a precaution.

08:55.852 --> 08:56.817
Well, as a precaution,

08:56.842 --> 08:57.841
you are going to get it
checked out,

08:57.866 --> 08:59.399
because that may need
to be drained.

08:59.424 --> 09:01.758
- [laughing]
- Look, Sam? Sam.

09:01.783 --> 09:03.683
This is serious.

09:03.708 --> 09:05.301
You know better.
Don't mess around.

09:05.326 --> 09:06.925
Okay. All right.

09:06.950 --> 09:08.717
I will get it looked at.

09:08.742 --> 09:11.056
Okay.
That's all I'm asking.

09:11.082 --> 09:12.548
[chuckles]

09:14.587 --> 09:16.120
- Ouch.
- You were right.

09:16.145 --> 09:18.412
Two-bone distal fracture,
moderately displaced.

09:18.437 --> 09:19.536
Needs to be plated.

09:19.561 --> 09:20.927
It didn't take
a diagnostic genius.

09:20.952 --> 09:22.885
Not with that
degree of deformity.

09:23.073 --> 09:24.740
- Mr. Blevins...
- I'm done here.

09:24.765 --> 09:26.067
Let 'em take me away.

09:26.092 --> 09:27.950
Well, I'm afraid, first,
you need surgery

09:27.975 --> 09:29.593
to realign
the bones in your arm.

09:29.660 --> 09:31.467
We're gonna have
an orthopedic surgeon

09:31.492 --> 09:34.293
- come down right now to...
- No. No surgery.

09:34.318 --> 09:35.551
[coughing]

09:35.576 --> 09:37.915
Well, without it, your arm
may not heal properly.

09:37.940 --> 09:39.362
You could have
a permanent deformity

09:39.387 --> 09:40.519
and reduced function.

09:40.521 --> 09:42.660
Put a cast on it.

09:42.685 --> 09:43.984
Mr. Blevins,
you want some water?

09:44.009 --> 09:47.644
No... no, what I want
is to be taken out of here.

09:48.716 --> 09:50.597
Put the cuffs...
[gurgles]

09:50.622 --> 09:51.879
Put the cuffs on!

09:51.904 --> 09:54.231
- Whoa. Mr. Blevins.
- [coughs]

09:54.256 --> 09:55.346
[screams]
Okay.

09:55.371 --> 09:56.823
I need...
[screams]

09:56.848 --> 09:58.147
All right, I need suction.

09:58.172 --> 09:59.722
Get a crash cart
and have atropine ready

09:59.747 --> 10:00.880
in case his heart rate drops.

10:00.905 --> 10:02.938
We are not losing this guy.

10:06.704 --> 10:08.204
Where is he?
Where is Walter?

10:08.229 --> 10:10.302
We are running a few tests
right now.

10:10.327 --> 10:12.360
When he's done,
I can take you to him.

10:12.363 --> 10:15.297
Oh, Dr. Halstead,
this is Mrs. Blevins.

10:15.299 --> 10:17.900
Please, someone tell me
what's going on.

10:17.902 --> 10:19.869
Your husband
was in a car accident.

10:19.871 --> 10:21.670
He has a badly broken arm

10:21.672 --> 10:22.972
and in the last half hour

10:22.974 --> 10:24.540
he began coughing up blood

10:24.542 --> 10:26.842
- and passed out.
- Oh, my God!

10:26.844 --> 10:29.311
Is Walter being treated
for any illnesses?

10:29.313 --> 10:31.881
No.
No, he's... he's fine.

10:31.883 --> 10:34.683
- I need to see him.
- Okay.

10:34.685 --> 10:36.685
I can take you to his room.

10:40.458 --> 10:43.692
Excuse me. Um, Mrs. Blevins?
My name's Jay Halstead.

10:43.694 --> 10:45.594
I'm a detective with
the Chicago Police Department.

10:45.596 --> 10:47.897
I need to ask you a few
questions about your husband.

10:47.899 --> 10:49.532
Why are the police involved?

10:49.534 --> 10:51.300
I thought Walter
was in an accident.

10:51.302 --> 10:52.568
Uh, yes.

10:52.570 --> 10:54.336
He was driving a car
that he stole.

10:54.338 --> 10:56.446
- At gunpoint.
- What?

10:56.471 --> 10:58.505
There's multiple witnesses.

10:58.620 --> 11:01.137
That son of a bitch.

11:01.420 --> 11:03.453
I'm sorry.
Ma'am?

11:03.614 --> 11:05.014
My husband is no angel.

11:05.016 --> 11:06.348
I knew that when I married him,

11:06.350 --> 11:09.919
but he has been straight
for 18 years.

11:09.921 --> 11:11.754
Has a job, a kid,

11:11.756 --> 11:14.056
and now, out of the blue,
he throws it all away?

11:14.058 --> 11:16.125
I warned him, if he ever
committed another crime,

11:16.127 --> 11:17.359
I would leave him,
and that is exactly

11:17.384 --> 11:18.454
what I'm going to do.

11:18.479 --> 11:20.479
What do you want to know?

11:20.504 --> 11:22.471
Um, why don't we go
sit down somewhere?

11:22.496 --> 11:24.496
Yeah.

11:28.472 --> 11:30.406
I'm looking for a Robert Parker.

11:30.408 --> 11:31.807
Bobby's in Treatment 3.

11:31.809 --> 11:33.709
Wha... who called
for a psych consult?

11:33.711 --> 11:35.878
The attending,
Dr. Movitt.

11:35.880 --> 11:37.379
- Why?
- I know Bobby.

11:37.381 --> 11:38.647
Treated him for a month now.

11:38.649 --> 11:39.882
He's just really kind.

11:39.884 --> 11:42.251
Huh.
I guess there's some concern

11:42.253 --> 11:43.719
that he can't
take care of himself?

11:43.721 --> 11:45.154
Because he gave
some clothes away?

11:45.156 --> 11:46.622
He just likes to help people.

11:46.624 --> 11:50.559
Oh,
just gonna have a little chat.

11:51.863 --> 11:53.629
He is such a good nurser.

11:53.631 --> 11:55.641
I think it took Jeff
three or four days

11:55.666 --> 11:58.334
to actually get the hang of it.

11:58.336 --> 12:00.736
- He's so beautiful.
- Mm-hmm.

12:00.738 --> 12:02.872
Oh, look at this.

12:02.874 --> 12:04.740
I couldn't resist.

12:04.742 --> 12:07.418
A little something for him
to wear on the way home.

12:07.443 --> 12:08.695
Isn't that cute?

12:08.720 --> 12:12.058
Oh, I think he's finished.

12:12.083 --> 12:13.515
Oh, you think he is?

12:13.517 --> 12:14.950
Here. I'll get him.

12:14.952 --> 12:18.520
You come here.
You come here to me.

12:18.522 --> 12:22.358
- Yeah. Oh.
- [baby coos]

12:22.360 --> 12:25.661
Oh.
[chuckles]

12:25.663 --> 12:27.162
You know, my parents emailed.

12:27.164 --> 12:28.430
They should be here soon.

12:28.432 --> 12:29.798
Oh.

12:29.823 --> 12:32.940
Well, they'll be so happy
to see the baby.

12:32.965 --> 12:34.882
They must miss you terribly.

12:34.906 --> 12:38.173
Yeah, they complain
about it all the time.

12:38.175 --> 12:42.544
Always asking when I'm gonna
move back to Seattle.

12:42.546 --> 12:46.015
- Do you ever think about that?
- Oh, yeah,

12:46.017 --> 12:47.616
but I want to finish
my fellowship.

12:47.618 --> 12:51.086
Oh.
Well, you met Jeff here.

12:51.088 --> 12:53.022
You must have a lot
of good memories here.

12:53.024 --> 12:54.623
Of course I do.

12:54.625 --> 12:56.525
I mean, I know the weather's
not good in Chicago,

12:56.527 --> 13:00.462
but Seattle, ugh.
That rain?

13:00.464 --> 13:03.365
I'd get depressed.

13:05.102 --> 13:06.402
What do you think?

13:06.404 --> 13:08.437
So, uh, how long you been
living at the shelter, Bobby?

13:08.439 --> 13:10.406
Uh, about two months now.

13:10.408 --> 13:12.074
And where were you before that?

13:12.076 --> 13:13.842
At home.
Uh, Lincoln Park.

13:13.844 --> 13:15.177
Ooh, nice neighborhood.

13:15.179 --> 13:17.046
Shelter must have been
quite a change.

13:17.048 --> 13:18.547
I don't mind.

13:18.549 --> 13:20.482
The people there need me.

13:20.484 --> 13:21.684
I don't have much anymore,

13:21.686 --> 13:23.953
but what I do have,
I'm happy to give.

13:23.955 --> 13:25.955
And what prompted you
to make the move

13:25.957 --> 13:27.589
from Lincoln Park?

13:27.591 --> 13:29.358
It's my wife's idea.

13:29.360 --> 13:31.293
She said I was giving away
all of our savings.

13:31.295 --> 13:33.195
Bankrupting the family.

13:33.197 --> 13:35.364
She didn't know
what happened to me.

13:35.366 --> 13:36.832
Why I changed.

13:36.834 --> 13:38.834
Uh, tell me how you changed.

13:38.836 --> 13:41.770
[chuckles]
I used to be a regular guy.

13:41.772 --> 13:44.345
Corporate job, a house,
a couple of cars.

13:44.370 --> 13:47.176
One morning I woke up,

13:47.178 --> 13:49.845
and I realized that
the only thing I wanted to do,

13:49.847 --> 13:52.247
the only thing that mattered,

13:52.249 --> 13:54.116
was helping other people.

13:54.118 --> 13:55.918
Giving whatever I had to them.

13:55.920 --> 13:59.788
Any idea of the, uh...
The source of this inspiration?

13:59.790 --> 14:02.925
You mean did God talk to me?
Or an angel?

14:02.927 --> 14:06.495
No, no, I...
I just knew...

14:06.497 --> 14:08.497
inside.

14:09.767 --> 14:11.867
I can barely see it.

14:11.869 --> 14:13.602
It's the gray spot right here.

14:13.604 --> 14:15.037
That's the hematoma.

14:15.039 --> 14:16.538
We often see it in car crashes.

14:16.540 --> 14:17.940
When the seatbelt you were
wearing tightened,

14:17.942 --> 14:19.942
it caused a deep bruise
around your intestine.

14:19.944 --> 14:22.729
So I'm, like, bleeding inside?

14:22.754 --> 14:24.179
Not anymore.

14:24.181 --> 14:26.081
Blood's clotted now,
formed a solid mass,

14:26.083 --> 14:28.283
causing the swelling and pain
you're feeling in your stomach.

14:28.285 --> 14:29.944
The swelling should go down
in a couple days.

14:29.969 --> 14:31.587
For the next few hours,
we'll continue to monitor you.

14:31.589 --> 14:33.122
So sit tight, all right?

14:33.124 --> 14:35.157
What about Jess?

14:35.159 --> 14:37.659
She's still in ICU.

14:39.597 --> 14:42.031
We met at this coffee shop,

14:42.033 --> 14:43.699
but it was too crowded,

14:43.701 --> 14:47.002
so I suggested we drive
to one a few miles away.

14:48.172 --> 14:50.172
That's when it happened.

14:52.043 --> 14:54.443
Can I see her?

14:54.445 --> 14:56.311
I'll have a nurse
take you up to ICU

14:56.313 --> 14:58.847
once Jess has been cleared
for visitors.

14:58.849 --> 15:01.784
- Thanks.
- Sure.

15:05.156 --> 15:07.122
And initial there, please.

15:07.124 --> 15:08.991
And sign here
to acknowledge receipt.

15:08.993 --> 15:10.628
That's two bags HLA-matched

15:10.653 --> 15:12.185
bone marrow-regenerating stem cells

15:12.210 --> 15:14.678
- for patient Christy Pierce.
- Thank you.

15:14.703 --> 15:16.703
Careful with these.

15:17.859 --> 15:19.158
Thanks.

15:19.183 --> 15:22.050
Fingers crossed.

15:22.075 --> 15:23.642
Sharon.

15:25.896 --> 15:28.030
I'm sorry to have to tell you
this, believe me.

15:28.055 --> 15:29.321
Tell me what?

15:29.346 --> 15:31.113
The hospital's decided
to shut down

15:31.115 --> 15:32.848
Christy Pierce's transplant.

15:32.850 --> 15:33.982
What?

15:33.984 --> 15:35.684
Have you seen these?

15:35.686 --> 15:37.539
Yeah, Christy's brother
put them up.

15:37.564 --> 15:39.007
He organized a fundraiser.

15:39.032 --> 15:40.622
For Christy's donor.

15:40.624 --> 15:42.825
And the hospital is concerned
about the appearance

15:42.827 --> 15:44.760
of an individual being
compensated

15:44.762 --> 15:46.285
for donating an organ, which...

15:46.310 --> 15:48.297
Violates federal law.
I know that,

15:48.299 --> 15:50.132
but no one's being paid.

15:50.134 --> 15:51.767
The donor agreed months ago.

15:51.769 --> 15:53.702
Well, it still puts
the hospital and its staff

15:53.704 --> 15:55.704
at risk for hefty fines,

15:55.706 --> 15:57.239
sanctions,
I mean, even imprisonment.

15:57.241 --> 16:00.242
It's a kid doing a good deed.

16:00.244 --> 16:02.038
- He's a minor.
- It doesn't matter.

16:02.063 --> 16:03.812
These flyers have put us
in an impossible situation.

16:03.814 --> 16:05.829
Well how about Christy's
impossible situation?

16:05.854 --> 16:08.755
- Maggie.
- It...

16:09.732 --> 16:11.232
Christy has just gone through

16:11.257 --> 16:14.758
five days of chemotherapy
and radiation.

16:14.802 --> 16:17.136
Her body has been ravaged

16:17.161 --> 16:19.428
in preparation
for this transplant.

16:19.430 --> 16:22.620
Without it, she will die.

16:23.077 --> 16:25.044
- It's out of my hands.
- No, Peter,

16:25.069 --> 16:26.916
it's still in your hands.

16:26.941 --> 16:28.808
Find a way to fix this.

16:28.833 --> 16:30.866
I will do my best,
but the law does not give me

16:30.891 --> 16:33.258
a lot of room to maneuver
on this.

16:33.283 --> 16:36.318
You need to look
for another donor.

16:38.315 --> 16:40.349
[sighs]

16:44.492 --> 16:45.959
I don't understand.

16:45.961 --> 16:48.120
They can't just
shut the transplant down.

16:48.145 --> 16:49.193
They can't do that.

16:49.218 --> 16:52.115
I'm sorry, Kathleen.
They can and they have.

16:52.140 --> 16:54.516
No, there must be
something you can do.

16:54.541 --> 16:56.946
We're exploring
our legal options,

16:56.971 --> 16:58.771
but the only thing
we can do right now

16:58.796 --> 17:00.622
is look for another donor

17:00.647 --> 17:02.013
which we're doing.

17:02.015 --> 17:03.780
Wha... what if we promise

17:03.805 --> 17:05.493
not to give any of the proceeds
to the donor?

17:05.519 --> 17:09.487
Unfortunately, the intent
was to give a financial gift

17:09.512 --> 17:12.500
to the donor, which is enough

17:12.525 --> 17:13.894
in the eyes of the law.

17:13.919 --> 17:16.151
Intent?

17:16.175 --> 17:18.006
Are these lawyers
gonna go in there

17:18.008 --> 17:20.642
and tell my daughter that intent

17:20.666 --> 17:22.503
is more important than she is?

17:22.529 --> 17:24.714
Are they willing to let her die?

17:24.739 --> 17:26.571
Do you want me
to break the news to Christy?

17:26.597 --> 17:28.463
No.

17:30.320 --> 17:32.887
I'm her mother.

17:32.912 --> 17:35.713
I'll tell her.

