17:44.707 --> 17:47.974
Mr. Blevins,
how are you feeling?

17:48.104 --> 17:49.704
I hope that means better.

17:49.729 --> 17:52.430
Has anything like that
ever happened before?

17:52.432 --> 17:54.098
How's the couple I hit?

17:54.100 --> 17:56.467
She's in the ICU.
We're monitoring him.

17:56.469 --> 17:58.436
Can they take me away now?

17:58.438 --> 17:59.768
First, we need to discuss

17:59.793 --> 18:01.259
the results of your chest X-ray.

18:01.284 --> 18:02.450
[sighs]

18:02.475 --> 18:04.121
We discovered a mass,

18:04.146 --> 18:06.246
approximately two centimeters
in diameter,

18:06.279 --> 18:08.212
in the left lobe of your lungs.

18:08.214 --> 18:09.647
Now, a finding like that,

18:09.649 --> 18:11.449
in conjunction with
coughing blood...

18:11.451 --> 18:14.185
I'm concerned.

18:14.187 --> 18:16.153
We need a CT scan, and then
a possible biopsy...

18:16.155 --> 18:18.022
Don't bother.

18:18.024 --> 18:19.357
Well, we really should
determine...

18:19.359 --> 18:21.926
It's cancer.

18:23.410 --> 18:26.111
I've known about it
for a few months.

18:27.700 --> 18:29.300
When I spoke with
your wife earlier,

18:29.302 --> 18:31.402
she didn't mention
that you were diagnosed.

18:31.404 --> 18:34.071
She doesn't know about it.

18:35.575 --> 18:37.100
Well, have you started
treatment, or...

18:37.125 --> 18:38.509
Look, you've run
your little test.

18:38.511 --> 18:40.478
You've checked all the boxes,
but now,

18:40.480 --> 18:42.747
I just want the cops
to get me out of here.

18:42.749 --> 18:44.561
Well, I can't release
you until I'm sure

18:44.586 --> 18:47.476
you're stable enough for jail.

18:47.501 --> 18:50.102
Well, do what you have to.

18:51.868 --> 18:53.635
All right.

18:53.660 --> 18:57.295
Don't tell my wife about this.

19:01.988 --> 19:03.855
[sighs]

19:03.880 --> 19:06.814
<i>[monitors beeping]</i>

19:16.678 --> 19:19.846
[whispers] Jess.

19:24.280 --> 19:26.881
Mike.

19:28.520 --> 19:32.388
I wanted to see how you were.

19:38.471 --> 19:41.848
How are you feeling?

19:46.690 --> 19:49.023
Oh, he smells like heaven.

19:49.048 --> 19:50.548
Think he knows me?

19:50.550 --> 19:51.849
Of course he does.

19:51.851 --> 19:52.777
<i>[door opening]</i>

19:52.802 --> 19:54.149
- Hello!
- [gasps]

19:54.174 --> 19:55.907
Mom!

19:55.932 --> 19:57.632
- Hello, sweetheart.
- Hi, Daddy.

19:57.657 --> 20:00.417
Helen.
Hello, Helen. Congratulations.

20:00.442 --> 20:03.304
[gasp]
Oh, let me hold him.

20:03.329 --> 20:05.096
Well, he... he's asleep.

20:05.098 --> 20:06.931
Oh, yes, he is.
Yes, he is.

20:06.933 --> 20:09.468
Oh, yes you are.
Yes, you are.

20:09.493 --> 20:12.146
Look at this beautiful boy.

20:12.171 --> 20:14.505
Can you believe
we're grandparents?

20:14.507 --> 20:17.475
Oh, I think he has
your daddy's mouth.

20:17.477 --> 20:18.876
- You think?
- Watch his head.

20:18.878 --> 20:21.045
- Oh, here. Here he is.
- Oh, my goodness.

20:21.047 --> 20:22.566
Oh.

20:22.591 --> 20:25.526
Oh, wait till
Auntie and Uncle Cliff meet him.

20:25.752 --> 20:26.851
We're putting a crib
in your room

20:26.853 --> 20:28.819
for when you and Owen
come to visit.

20:28.821 --> 20:30.888
Just don't take down
my Nick Carter poster, okay?

20:30.890 --> 20:33.867
- We won't. We promise.
- Good. Right.

20:33.892 --> 20:35.772
Dr. Charles.

20:35.797 --> 20:37.930
I heard Bobby was upstairs
getting a CT?

20:37.955 --> 20:39.655
Yeah, just want to rule out

20:39.680 --> 20:42.681
any organic cause
for his behavior, that's all.

20:42.706 --> 20:43.888
You think he's crazy?

20:43.888 --> 20:45.488
You mean like delusional
or psychotic?

20:45.490 --> 20:46.509
Not at all.

20:46.534 --> 20:48.301
Quite rational, in fact.

20:48.326 --> 20:50.159
Then why the CT?

20:50.161 --> 20:53.496
Actions are a little
obsessive, if not compulsive.

20:53.498 --> 20:54.797
You know, giving your shoes away

20:54.799 --> 20:57.199
in Chicago
in the middle of the winter?

20:57.201 --> 20:58.868
You've, um...

20:58.870 --> 21:01.837
taken quite an interest
in Mr. Parker, haven't you?

21:01.839 --> 21:03.139
Yeah, I guess I have.

21:03.141 --> 21:06.108
It's...
never mind.

21:07.759 --> 21:09.725
Try me.

21:11.783 --> 21:13.649
St. Francis.

21:13.651 --> 21:15.718
He reminds me of St. Francis.

21:15.720 --> 21:18.120
- I was raised Catholic.
- Ah.

21:18.122 --> 21:19.755
And growing up, we had
this little statue

21:19.757 --> 21:21.624
of San Francisco in the garden.

21:21.626 --> 21:23.392
Of all the saints,
he was my favorite.

21:23.394 --> 21:24.945
He gave away all his money,

21:24.970 --> 21:26.596
all his possessions,
to the poor.

21:26.598 --> 21:29.298
Took care of the sick
with no thought of himself.

21:29.300 --> 21:30.933
Remarkable fella.

21:30.935 --> 21:33.402
I'm not saying Bobby
is an actual saint,

21:33.404 --> 21:36.138
but... saintly?

21:36.140 --> 21:38.274
Yeah.

21:38.276 --> 21:39.842
We're just...
Want to make sure

21:39.844 --> 21:42.044
we're doing the right thing
by him, that's all.

21:42.046 --> 21:44.580
Yeah.

21:47.619 --> 21:49.051
- Boss?
- Yeah?

21:49.053 --> 21:51.020
Peter Kalmick's in Treatment 4.

21:51.022 --> 21:53.589
- What?
- Mm-hmm.

21:55.660 --> 21:57.326
What happened?

21:57.328 --> 21:59.095
I've been getting
these pounding headaches.

21:59.097 --> 22:01.230
His blood pressure spiked.

22:01.232 --> 22:03.065
Dr. Movitt put him
on a nipride drip.

22:03.067 --> 22:06.068
- Pressure's coming down.
- Thank you.

22:11.342 --> 22:12.742
Christy Pierce,

22:12.744 --> 22:14.377
there's nothing I can do.

22:14.379 --> 22:17.747
You understand why the sale
of human organs is illegal.

22:17.749 --> 22:19.208
Once they have monetary value,

22:19.233 --> 22:20.583
at best,
poor people will sell them.

22:20.585 --> 22:22.029
At worst, people will get
killed for them.

22:22.054 --> 22:23.353
I get all that.

22:23.421 --> 22:24.854
How about you try this?

22:24.856 --> 22:26.653
Bone marrow is not an organ.

22:26.678 --> 22:29.068
According to the National
Organ Transplant Act, it is.

22:29.093 --> 22:30.526
But that's wrong.

22:30.528 --> 22:34.050
A donor's marrow regenerates
itself within two weeks.

22:34.075 --> 22:35.608
It's just like giving blood.

22:35.633 --> 22:37.266
Come on, Sharon.
I've done my homework.

22:37.268 --> 22:39.568
In 2011, the Ninth Circuit
Court of Appeals

22:39.570 --> 22:42.104
ruled that bone marrow donors
can be compensated

22:42.106 --> 22:44.530
because the cells are
blood parts, not organ parts.

22:44.555 --> 22:45.675
So what's the problem?

22:45.677 --> 22:47.209
The problem is that that's
the Ninth Circuit.

22:47.211 --> 22:50.212
It's Arizona, Montana.
We're in Illinois, the Seventh.

22:50.214 --> 22:51.981
It hasn't ruled.

22:51.983 --> 22:53.716
Look...
[sighs]

22:53.718 --> 22:56.052
I shouldn't just gone into
estate planning like my brother.

22:56.054 --> 22:57.887
It's so much less stressful.

22:57.889 --> 23:00.256
I'm sorry you're suffering,
Peter,

23:00.258 --> 23:02.792
but your stress is nothing

23:02.817 --> 23:06.385
compared to
what's going on upstairs.

23:09.100 --> 23:12.168
- <i>[alarm blares]
- Help!</i>

23:12.170 --> 23:14.670
- That's Jess's room.
- She must have thrown a clot.

23:14.672 --> 23:16.038
Help him, please. Somebody!

23:16.040 --> 23:17.640
He was complaining of
abdominal pain.

23:17.674 --> 23:19.073
- CT showed a duodenal hematoma.
- Oh, Mike!

23:19.098 --> 23:20.877
- Mike...
- Ah!

23:20.902 --> 23:22.168
It must've ruptured.

23:22.193 --> 23:23.559
We need to get him
up to the OR, now.

23:23.584 --> 23:25.284
- Yes, Doctor.
- Is he gonna be all right?

23:25.309 --> 23:28.143
We'll do our best.

23:28.152 --> 23:29.685
[grunts]

23:35.116 --> 23:37.016
There's too much blood.
More suction.

23:37.041 --> 23:38.541
Suction.

23:40.801 --> 23:42.734
There's food particles
mixed in with his blood.

23:42.759 --> 23:44.492
Slow down,
it won't do you any good

23:44.494 --> 23:45.960
if you make the injury bigger.

23:45.962 --> 23:48.029
If he bleeds out,
it won't help me, either.

23:48.031 --> 23:50.398
It's a big duodenal hematoma

23:50.400 --> 23:52.567
with pretty brisk bleeding
along the anterior perforation.

23:52.592 --> 23:53.248
Stitch?

23:53.273 --> 23:55.264
The lac extends
into the second portion.

23:55.289 --> 23:59.124
- I can see that.
- Stay clear of the ampulla.

23:59.149 --> 24:01.953
What did the Ortho say
about the elbow?

24:01.978 --> 24:04.479
Just concentrate
on your surgery.

24:04.481 --> 24:05.506
Did he drain it?

24:05.531 --> 24:07.245
Make sure you close
transversely.

24:07.270 --> 24:08.303
- I got it.
- In two layers.

24:08.328 --> 24:09.378
I know what I'm doing.

24:09.403 --> 24:10.936
Don't take that tone with me,
Dr. Rhodes.

24:10.961 --> 24:13.521
I'm your attending.

24:14.587 --> 24:16.549
Right.

24:18.297 --> 24:20.197
Close him up.

24:20.222 --> 24:23.523
Unless Dr. Zanetti
would prefer to.

24:29.803 --> 24:31.803
Helen?

24:34.223 --> 24:36.390
Maggie.

24:36.623 --> 24:39.257
Why are you out here
and not with Natalie?

24:39.282 --> 24:41.416
Oh, um,

24:41.418 --> 24:43.951
her... her parents
flew in from Seattle,

24:43.953 --> 24:47.822
so...
they're in there with her.

24:47.824 --> 24:49.891
Okay.

24:49.893 --> 24:52.794
- [sobs]
- Oh.

25:00.847 --> 25:02.847
[whimpers]

25:04.311 --> 25:07.579
Je... Jeff was my...
My only child,

25:07.604 --> 25:09.570
and...

25:09.595 --> 25:12.797
and his dad and I divorced
when he was three.

25:12.816 --> 25:15.416
He's remarried and...

25:15.441 --> 25:18.809
lives in Arizona someplace.

25:20.095 --> 25:22.729
The rest of my family is...

25:22.754 --> 25:24.387
gone.

25:24.412 --> 25:27.579
Jeff is gone...

25:27.604 --> 25:30.672
and Natalie and Owen...
[sobs]

25:30.700 --> 25:34.979
They're...
They're all I have.

25:35.004 --> 25:37.905
- They're all...
- Oh, honey.

25:37.907 --> 25:40.975
I don't want Natalie
and the baby go to Seattle.

25:40.977 --> 25:44.245
I'm selfish too.
I don't want Natalie to go.

25:44.270 --> 25:45.436
[sobbing]

25:47.917 --> 25:49.487
Hey there, Bobby.

25:49.512 --> 25:51.786
- Hey.
- Got your CT results back.

25:51.788 --> 25:54.255
I'd like to go over them
with you if you have a sec.

25:54.257 --> 25:55.890
- I can finish this later.
- No, no. Stay.

25:55.892 --> 25:57.358
It's... it's fine.

25:57.360 --> 25:59.193
So...

25:59.195 --> 26:01.395
when we talked before

26:01.397 --> 26:02.866
about the change you
experienced,

26:02.891 --> 26:04.657
you said that it was sudden.

26:04.667 --> 26:06.367
- Happened overnight.
- That's right.

26:06.369 --> 26:07.602
The abrupt nature of the change

26:07.604 --> 26:10.538
made me wonder if there might
be a physical cause.

26:10.540 --> 26:13.841
So here, I want you to take
a look at something.

26:13.843 --> 26:16.177
This...

26:16.179 --> 26:18.145
is an image of a typical brain.

26:18.147 --> 26:20.948
And this...
is yours.

26:20.950 --> 26:22.683
Why does it look different?

26:22.685 --> 26:27.121
Because you, my friend,
had a stroke.

26:28.229 --> 26:30.596
That's...
I know stroke victims.

26:30.621 --> 26:32.206
They're... they're crippled
or can't speak.

26:32.231 --> 26:34.506
There are actually many
different kinds of strokes.

26:34.531 --> 26:37.331
Yours caused lesions to form
in the frontal lobe.

26:37.333 --> 26:38.933
That's the region of the brain
that controls,

26:38.935 --> 26:41.802
among many other things,
behavior and judgment.

26:41.804 --> 26:43.604
So you're saying
I'm brain damaged?

26:43.606 --> 26:45.439
I'm saying that,
in your instance,

26:45.441 --> 26:47.308
the stroke didn't cause
any physical impairment,

26:47.310 --> 26:48.776
but it did cause you to become

26:48.778 --> 26:50.822
what, clinically,

26:50.847 --> 26:54.449
I would describe as
pathologically generous.

26:54.474 --> 26:57.608
Making you compulsively
driven to give.

26:57.620 --> 27:00.821
So I help people
because of damage to my brain?

27:00.823 --> 27:01.989
Basically, yeah.

27:01.991 --> 27:04.358
But it feels good.
It makes me happy.

27:04.360 --> 27:06.727
Makes sense.

27:06.729 --> 27:08.529
I... I...

27:08.531 --> 27:09.797
don't want you to fix it.

27:09.799 --> 27:12.203
Well, that's fortunate because,

27:12.228 --> 27:13.260
truthfully, even if you did,

27:13.285 --> 27:15.785
aside from some
behavioral therapy,

27:15.810 --> 27:18.578
- we can't.
- Okay.

27:18.608 --> 27:21.042
Okay.

27:21.044 --> 27:22.577
I got back in touch
with the shelter.

27:22.579 --> 27:23.911
They're happy to have you back.

27:23.913 --> 27:24.879
In case you didn't know,
you've become

27:24.881 --> 27:26.581
something of a star there.

27:26.583 --> 27:28.449
Do you mind if I share
some details of your condition

27:28.451 --> 27:30.551
so that they can
help take care of you?

27:30.553 --> 27:32.520
- Sure.
- Great.

27:35.437 --> 27:37.637
[chuckles]

27:37.662 --> 27:39.562
Please call me
if there are any changes.

27:39.587 --> 27:41.654
Thank you.

27:41.698 --> 27:43.764
Was that the National Registry?

27:43.766 --> 27:46.245
So far no matches,
but we're in touch

27:46.270 --> 27:48.202
with every donor network
in the region.

27:48.227 --> 27:49.581
- We're not giving up.
- Mom!

27:49.606 --> 27:50.771
What is it?

27:50.773 --> 27:52.206
Something's wrong with Christy.

27:52.208 --> 27:54.208
Oh, God.

27:54.210 --> 27:55.610
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:55.612 --> 27:58.546
[monitor beeping rapidly]

27:58.548 --> 28:00.481
- No, Christy!
- No, no, no.

28:00.483 --> 28:03.284
We should stay out here.

28:03.286 --> 28:07.855
<i>♪
♪</i>

28:07.857 --> 28:09.857
[whimpers] No.

28:10.931 --> 28:12.397
[crying]

28:12.422 --> 28:14.188
Mr. Blevins is stable.

28:14.213 --> 28:15.546
I'm gonna go grab
a cup of coffee.

28:15.565 --> 28:17.231
Take that basket to Natalie,
would you?

28:17.233 --> 28:19.200
Radiology sent it.

28:20.203 --> 28:22.203
- Maggie?
- Uh-huh.

28:22.205 --> 28:23.704
You know,

28:23.706 --> 28:25.539
I don't want to give anyone
the wrong impression.

28:25.541 --> 28:26.907
The wrong impression?

28:26.909 --> 28:28.643
Natalie just had a baby.

28:28.645 --> 28:30.911
Oh. Uh-huh.
I know that.

28:30.913 --> 28:32.880
Her husband died
only six months ago.

28:32.882 --> 28:34.482
I know that too.

28:34.484 --> 28:37.485
So, I don't want to give
anyone the wrong impression.

28:37.487 --> 28:41.122
It amazes me
how dumb a doctor can be.

28:42.592 --> 28:46.827
Everybody knows
you like Natalie.

28:46.829 --> 28:48.229
They do?

28:48.231 --> 28:50.085
So, don't make things
too complicated.

28:50.110 --> 28:52.944
Just take the basket.

28:58.251 --> 29:00.518
[baby coos]

29:00.543 --> 29:02.476
From your fans in radiology.

29:02.478 --> 29:04.845
Well, hey there, stranger.

29:04.847 --> 29:06.247
What can I tell you?

29:06.249 --> 29:07.748
These crazy sick people
just keep

29:07.750 --> 29:09.817
rolling into the ED.

29:09.819 --> 29:12.586
Owen started to think
you forgot about him.

29:12.588 --> 29:14.422
Pretty sure the only thing
he thinks about

29:14.424 --> 29:15.856
is his next hit of dairy.

29:15.858 --> 29:17.425
[laughs]

29:17.427 --> 29:20.094
So, tell me what's been
going on downstairs.

29:20.096 --> 29:21.429
You want to talk shop?

29:21.431 --> 29:23.698
I'm desperate.

29:25.134 --> 29:27.716
Well, I do have
this one patient.

29:27.741 --> 29:29.303
He...

29:29.305 --> 29:30.538
Hi, Will.

29:30.540 --> 29:32.339
Hi, Mrs. Manning.

29:32.341 --> 29:34.108
Oh, please. Call me Helen.

29:34.110 --> 29:35.576
I'm so glad you came up.

29:35.578 --> 29:37.445
Natalie's been looking for you.

29:37.447 --> 29:39.213
Oh, don't guilt him out, Helen.

29:39.215 --> 29:42.383
I'm afraid I'm good at that.

29:43.486 --> 29:45.853
You're a Chicago boy,
aren't you, Will?

29:45.855 --> 29:47.788
Canaryville.
Three generations.

29:47.790 --> 29:50.357
We used to live out
in Canaryville. South Aberdeen.

29:50.359 --> 29:51.179
- Okay.
- Wait.

29:51.204 --> 29:52.336
You guys are talking, so...

29:52.361 --> 29:53.594
You know, Mom and Dad
just went down

29:53.596 --> 29:54.795
to the cafeteria to grab a bite

29:54.797 --> 29:55.963
if you want to join them.

29:55.965 --> 29:57.565
Oh, yeah, I'll do that.

29:57.567 --> 29:59.667
Great.

30:02.772 --> 30:03.938
What's up with her?

30:03.940 --> 30:05.039
What do you mean?

30:05.041 --> 30:07.274
Yesterday
she wasn't so friendly.

30:07.276 --> 30:08.642
It's the birth.

30:08.644 --> 30:10.144
It was very stressful for her.

30:10.146 --> 30:11.412
Yeah.

30:11.414 --> 30:13.314
All right,
tell me about this patient.

30:13.316 --> 30:15.216
Okay, so,
he was in a car accident.

30:15.218 --> 30:17.844
Severely fractured arm,
lung cancer,

30:17.869 --> 30:18.986
and as soon as I discharge him,

30:18.965 --> 30:20.398
he's going to jail.

30:20.423 --> 30:22.757
Oh, and his wife just left him.

30:22.759 --> 30:24.892
Ooh, sounds like a country song.

30:24.894 --> 30:27.762
- Yeah. Pretty hopeless case.
- Hmm.

30:27.764 --> 30:29.196
Well, the one thing
he's got going for him.

30:29.198 --> 30:30.464
At least in prison,

30:30.466 --> 30:33.234
he'll get the treatment
that he needs.

30:33.236 --> 30:36.137
Yeah, he will.

30:38.015 --> 30:40.449
<i>[elevator bell dings]</i>

30:40.474 --> 30:42.107
- Hey.
- Hey.

30:42.132 --> 30:43.598
About what happened
in the OR today...

30:43.623 --> 30:45.189
Pro forma, I was acting as your

30:45.214 --> 30:46.958
supervising attending physician.

30:46.983 --> 30:48.449
I think maybe
it was more than that.

30:48.451 --> 30:50.484
Look, Sam, you're a surgeon,
that's who you are,

30:50.486 --> 30:52.653
and right now,
you can't operate.

30:52.655 --> 30:53.921
Oh, I see.

30:53.923 --> 30:55.914
So out of my frustration,
I laid into you.

30:55.939 --> 30:56.399
Well...

30:56.424 --> 30:57.992
Couldn't possibly have
anything to do

30:57.994 --> 31:00.394
with you or your performance,
it's just me.

31:00.396 --> 31:01.726
I'm the crazy bitch.

31:01.751 --> 31:03.330
Aw, come on. Look.

31:03.355 --> 31:04.742
You're taking this
the wrong way.

31:04.767 --> 31:07.134
You are such a macho cliché.

31:07.136 --> 31:08.636
Sam, you put yourself at risk

31:08.638 --> 31:10.504
to do some serious damage
to your arm,

31:10.506 --> 31:11.872
and for what?

31:11.874 --> 31:14.542
This need to be the big,
mighty surgeon?

31:14.544 --> 31:15.876
You know that was stupid.

31:15.878 --> 31:17.545
You have this all figured out.

31:17.547 --> 31:20.447
You are so full of yourself.

31:20.449 --> 31:23.484
Come on, that's... that's
hilarious, coming from you.

31:23.486 --> 31:26.053
You know what, I think this
whole thing was a mistake.

31:26.055 --> 31:28.923
Yeah, I'm with you on that.

31:32.405 --> 31:34.572
Christy developed
staph myocarditis,

31:34.597 --> 31:36.630
causing her cardiovascular
system to collapse.

31:36.632 --> 31:38.999
Well, considering
her suppressed immune system,

31:39.001 --> 31:41.068
it was just a matter of time.

31:41.070 --> 31:42.251
How is she now?

31:42.276 --> 31:44.477
Antibiotics are controlling
the infection,

31:44.626 --> 31:46.459
but it's not a long-term fix.

31:46.484 --> 31:48.350
Only by giving her
a new immune system

31:48.377 --> 31:50.087
can the infection be eradicated.

31:50.112 --> 31:52.004
Otherwise...

31:52.029 --> 31:54.063
[sighs]

31:55.491 --> 31:57.524
Wait...

31:59.899 --> 32:01.933
Is Christy stable enough

32:01.958 --> 32:03.624
for the transplant?

32:03.626 --> 32:05.259
- You mean right now?
- Right now.

32:05.261 --> 32:07.962
Yeah, she is.

32:10.677 --> 32:14.612
Then do it.
Do the transplant.

32:14.637 --> 32:16.003
But the hospital shut it down.
We...

32:16.005 --> 32:18.372
Yes, I'm aware.

32:18.374 --> 32:20.708
Sharon, they'll have your job.
And legally, we...

32:20.733 --> 32:23.700
I will take full responsibility.

32:28.114 --> 32:30.348
All right, I'll prep the team.

32:30.373 --> 32:32.373
Thank you.

32:32.398 --> 32:35.399
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

32:35.424 --> 32:40.360
<i>♪
♪</i>

32:40.396 --> 32:43.379
Now, you got to promise
not to give these away.

32:43.404 --> 32:43.964
Okay.

32:43.966 --> 32:45.432
Or any other pieces of clothing.

32:45.434 --> 32:47.568
I don't want to see you
back here.

32:47.570 --> 32:49.970
I promise.
I'll be...

32:49.972 --> 32:52.316
I'll be...
Bobby? Bobby!

32:52.341 --> 32:54.007
Dr. Choi!

32:54.032 --> 32:56.733
<i>♪
♪</i>

32:56.758 --> 32:59.659
- He's stroking.
- Let's roll him on his side.

33:03.219 --> 33:05.252
<i>♪
♪</i>

33:07.808 --> 33:09.402
<i>[knocking on door]</i>

33:09.427 --> 33:11.827
Mr. Blevins?

33:12.135 --> 33:13.345
Mind if we talk?

33:13.370 --> 33:15.236
Nurse says I'm being discharged.

33:15.238 --> 33:17.112
Yeah, we're almost finished
with the paperwork.

33:17.137 --> 33:18.973
Then what's there to talk about?

33:18.975 --> 33:20.909
My brother. He's a cop.

33:20.911 --> 33:22.410
Good for you.

33:22.412 --> 33:25.146
He tells me stories about
dumb crimes people commit.

33:25.148 --> 33:26.981
He says there are no
smart criminals.

33:26.983 --> 33:29.083
If they were smart,
they wouldn't be criminals.

33:29.085 --> 33:31.953
Okay. And?

33:31.955 --> 33:34.522
I don't think
you're dumb, Walter.

33:34.524 --> 33:35.823
Yet you carjacked a woman

33:35.825 --> 33:39.761
right in front
of two police officers.

33:39.763 --> 33:42.497
When you first came in,
you said you were sorry.

33:42.499 --> 33:44.532
I think you really were.

33:44.534 --> 33:46.267
You never meant to hurt anyone.

33:46.269 --> 33:48.937
That wasn't part of your plan.

33:50.017 --> 33:53.418
You don't have health insurance.

33:55.656 --> 33:57.856
And without it, the cost of
surgery on your arm,

33:57.881 --> 33:59.647
that'd be pretty expensive.

33:59.649 --> 34:02.183
Not to mention the cost
of cancer treatments.

34:02.185 --> 34:05.353
Those could easily
exceed $200,000.

34:05.355 --> 34:07.922
Man, what do you want from me?

34:07.924 --> 34:10.158
You wanted to get caught...

34:10.159 --> 34:12.560
because in... in prison,

34:12.562 --> 34:15.295
health care is free.

34:15.297 --> 34:17.065
You don't owe me an answer,

34:17.067 --> 34:20.768
but your wife,

34:20.770 --> 34:22.770
she ought to know the truth.

34:25.998 --> 34:27.966
[sighs]

34:29.179 --> 34:31.913
Bobby suffered another
ischemic stroke,

34:31.915 --> 34:33.380
much more severe this time.

34:33.382 --> 34:34.916
His judgment remains impaired

34:34.918 --> 34:37.985
despite the medications
we've given him,

34:37.987 --> 34:40.221
and we have noticed

34:40.223 --> 34:41.856
further changes
to his temperament.

34:41.858 --> 34:44.225
- What kind of changes?
- They're profound.

34:44.226 --> 34:45.994
I've contacted DHS,
and they're gonna provide

34:45.996 --> 34:48.463
a guardian who can help Bobby

34:48.465 --> 34:51.666
get placed in a...
In a state-funded nursing home.

34:51.668 --> 34:54.268
I'm sorry, April.

35:00.176 --> 35:02.877
Hey, Bobby.

35:03.091 --> 35:04.390
Here, let me fill that
for you...

35:04.415 --> 35:05.413
It's mine.

35:05.415 --> 35:08.683
- I just want to fill it up...
- It's mine!

35:09.344 --> 35:11.544
Okay.

35:19.545 --> 35:21.545
Thank you.

35:24.334 --> 35:26.167
Vitals are stable.
Incision looks good.

35:26.169 --> 35:28.169
He's gonna be fine.
They both are.

35:28.171 --> 35:30.438
A few hours ago, they
didn't even know one another.

35:30.440 --> 35:32.407
Really?

35:32.409 --> 35:34.342
Yeah, wouldn't know it
to look at 'em.

35:34.344 --> 35:36.844
Shared trauma.
Saw it in the Navy.

35:36.846 --> 35:38.946
People who experience a life
and death situation together,

35:38.971 --> 35:40.492
- it creates a bond.
- Hm.

35:40.517 --> 35:41.816
Some kind of brain chemistry.

35:41.818 --> 35:44.728
I'm sure Dr. Charles
can explain it.

35:44.842 --> 35:46.742
Right, so what happens later?

35:46.767 --> 35:48.566
After they get back
to normal lives?

35:48.591 --> 35:50.091
Does it last?

35:50.116 --> 35:52.817
I have no idea.

35:55.358 --> 35:57.358
Doubt it.

36:10.047 --> 36:12.313
Nick, you'll have to say
"Happy Birthday" to your sister.

36:12.338 --> 36:13.704
It's not till summer.

36:13.716 --> 36:16.284
Well, when a patient
receives a transplant,

36:16.286 --> 36:17.919
we call that "Day Zero."

36:17.921 --> 36:20.688
So, in a way,
it's like a second birthday.

36:20.690 --> 36:23.257
We're so grateful, Sharon.

36:23.259 --> 36:24.926
What changed their minds?

36:24.928 --> 36:26.541
I think they just had to get

36:26.566 --> 36:29.466
their priorities straight.

36:35.814 --> 36:37.614
Don't start, Peter.
I know what I'm in for.

36:37.639 --> 36:40.607
Hey, hey.
I'm the bearer of good news.

36:42.038 --> 36:44.272
The hospital's not gonna
take action against you

36:44.297 --> 36:46.330
given the gravity
of the situation.

36:46.355 --> 36:48.822
"U.S. prosecutes hospital
administrator

36:48.824 --> 36:49.990
for saving girl's life."

36:49.992 --> 36:51.058
I don't think
the Justice Department

36:51.060 --> 36:52.993
needs that kind of publicity.

36:52.995 --> 36:54.895
So I think it is safe to assume

36:54.897 --> 36:56.263
you are in the clear.

36:56.265 --> 36:58.832
- Well, ain't that great.
- Sharon?

36:58.834 --> 37:00.434
A girl has to almost die

37:00.436 --> 37:02.459
for this hospital to realize

37:02.484 --> 37:05.279
that it's actually
here to treat patients?

37:05.304 --> 37:08.839
You stay on your
blood pressure meds, Peter.

37:12.414 --> 37:13.547
He puts cops' lives at risk

37:13.549 --> 37:14.848
and then he nearly gets
that couple killed

37:14.850 --> 37:15.949
so he can get free health care?

37:15.951 --> 37:17.684
They should let the guy rot.

37:17.686 --> 37:19.653
The guy was trying
to protect his family.

37:19.655 --> 37:22.055
Sure. Sure.

37:22.057 --> 37:23.557
Here's a stat for you.

37:23.559 --> 37:25.392
Health care expenses
account for over half

37:25.394 --> 37:27.977
of all bankruptcies
in the U.S.

37:28.195 --> 37:29.661
Be thankful you got
a great health plan.

37:29.686 --> 37:31.052
I hope you report this.

37:31.077 --> 37:33.044
Doctor/patient confidentiality

37:33.069 --> 37:35.503
and you're not gonna say
anything, either.

37:36.477 --> 37:39.345
This knucklehead ready
to be signed out?

37:39.370 --> 37:42.237
- Yeah.
- Okay, then.

37:45.748 --> 37:48.682
It isn't exactly
free health care, Jay.

37:48.684 --> 37:50.651
The guy is going to prison.

37:56.489 --> 37:59.816
[sighs]

38:03.065 --> 38:04.965
[sighs]

38:19.225 --> 38:21.659
Here. Hey...

38:32.389 --> 38:35.423
I got benched for two weeks.

38:39.234 --> 38:41.201
How about dinner?

38:41.203 --> 38:44.938
I'll even
cut your steak for you.

38:44.940 --> 38:46.473
[laughter]

38:46.475 --> 38:48.675
Okay.

38:49.712 --> 38:52.179
Okay.

38:52.181 --> 38:55.082
<i>[gentle music]</i>

38:55.084 --> 39:03.023
<i>♪
♪</i>

39:03.025 --> 39:04.891
- So you're off?
- Mm-hmm.

39:04.893 --> 39:06.326
All right.

39:06.328 --> 39:08.128
See you later, little man.

39:08.130 --> 39:09.229
Oh.

39:09.231 --> 39:10.797
Let me know
if you need anything.

39:10.799 --> 39:12.432
Thank you.

39:12.434 --> 39:14.167
All right.

39:14.169 --> 39:15.343
Helen.

39:15.368 --> 39:17.268
Will.

39:17.406 --> 39:20.006
You know, I think that Will's
a very nice man.

39:20.008 --> 39:21.675
Yeah, he is.

39:21.677 --> 39:23.677
Oh!

39:23.679 --> 39:25.679
Hi.
Dad's outside with the car.

39:25.681 --> 39:26.747
[baby talk]

39:26.772 --> 39:28.692
Okay, here we go.

39:28.717 --> 39:29.850
- Here we are.
- Cover him up.

39:29.852 --> 39:31.918
- Want me to take that?
- Oh, I'm good.

39:53.411 --> 39:55.611
He's gone.

39:55.636 --> 39:58.204
The Bobby I knew is gone.

39:58.229 --> 39:59.928
Hmm.

39:59.953 --> 40:02.454
I mean, maybe
he never really existed.

40:02.479 --> 40:04.161
I wanted to believe
that self-sacrifice

40:04.186 --> 40:05.652
came from the soul...

40:05.654 --> 40:08.255
And not lesions on the brain?

40:08.257 --> 40:10.791
I mean, what if there's
no such thing as saints?

40:10.793 --> 40:13.609
What if Mother Theresa,
Gandhi, Saint Francis...

40:13.634 --> 40:15.973
They all just...
were people who suffered

40:15.998 --> 40:18.398
- a stroke to the frontal lobe?
- Who knows?

40:18.400 --> 40:20.367
Theories abound.

40:20.369 --> 40:22.402
I mean, as a shrink,
I'm supposed to tell you that

40:22.404 --> 40:26.139
we project saintly qualities
onto others 'cause we need to.

40:26.141 --> 40:28.809
Makes us feel hopeful.
Safe.

40:28.811 --> 40:30.143
Hm.

40:30.145 --> 40:31.545
But this I know for certain:

40:31.547 --> 40:33.814
whoever those people
were or weren't,

40:33.816 --> 40:36.483
they absolutely
understood the power

40:36.485 --> 40:39.186
of a simple act
of human kindness.

40:39.188 --> 40:40.454
I guess I'm just trying
to figure out

40:40.456 --> 40:42.289
